Amorphophallus paeoniifolius

   [400.gif]
    Authority   (Dennst.) Nicolson
      Family    Liliopsida:Arecidae:Arecales:Palmae
     Synonyms   Amorphophallus campanulatus Blume
   Common names elephant foot yam, elephant yam, yam
      Editor
   Ecocrop code 400

   Notes
   BRIEF DESCRIPTION A herb growing up to 1.25 m in height. Its tubers are
   large, flattened yellow or brown, 20-25 cm in diameter, with central
   depression. The tubers are formed underground, 5-10 being produced from
   the main tuber. The leaf blads are 30-80 cm in length with a 50-80 cm
   long petiole. USES The tubers of cultivars with smooth leaf stalks are
   used as boiled vegetable, the calcium oxalate crystals present are
   removed by extensive washing or boiling. The young petrioles are used
   as a cooked vegetable. GROWING PERIOD Perennial herb. The crop matures
   in 220-350 days. The corms have a dormancy period of 60-90 days, and
   after 3 years of growth, the corms weigh 7-9 kg and are marketable.
   COMMON NAMES Elephant yam, Elephant foot yam, Giantarum, Sweet yam,
   Suran, Arsaghna, Balukund, Kidaran, Telinga potato, Zaminkund, Chena,
   Karak-kavanai, Ilis-ilis, Kand godda, Sooweg, Waloor, Anto, Oroy,
   Pangapong, Tigi, Koe, Konjac, Konniaku, Mo-yu. FURTHER INF Synonym:
   Amorphophallus campanulatus. Elephant yam grows wild in southeast Asia,
   extending to Java, the Philippines and the Pacific. Most production
   occurs at altitudes below 1000 m. Yields of 20 t/ha have been reported
   from India.

   Sources
   SOURCES E400
   Tindall H 1983 pp 50-52 [FER, DEP, TEXT, PH, DRA, TEMP, RAIN]
   Purseglove 1972 pp 59 [USE, LIMIT]

